<DOC><DOCNO> AP890311-0005 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-89 0214EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Belgium-Subway     03-11 0128</FIRST><SECOND>PM-BRF--Belgium-Subway,0130</SECOND><HEAD>Subway Crime Increased 26-Fold During 1980s</HEAD><DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Petty crime in the Brussels subway hasincreased 26-fold in the 1980s, but the Metro remains among thesafest subway systems in the world, transit authorities say.   Thefts of purses, money and jewelry in the trains and in thesubway's 57 stations surged to over 800 cases last year from 30 in1980. These and other petty crimes were 26.6 times as high last yearas in 1980.   But officials said Friday that no murder or rape has ever beencommitted in the subway system, which is used by 650,000 people eachday.   Subway vandalism also was reported on the rise. In 1988, thesubway system spent $100,000 repairing damage by graffiti writersand vandals.</TEXT></DOC>